Tens of thousands of people gathered in Paris on Saturday to rally against French President Emmanuel Macron and sweeping reforms that have characterized his administration. Authorities warned protesters against violating public order after May Day demonstrations witnessed rioting and clashes with police. Read more: Emmanuel Macron: French savior or tormentor? 'Down with the president' Read more: Is Emmanuel Macron Europe's new Angela Merkel? Macron has pushed through economic reforms that workers fear could undermine their rights Macron's controversial reforms: The protests are the latest expression of opposition to Macron's planned reforms to kick-start the French economy after years of tepid growth and stubbornly high unemployment. The centrist president wants to overhaul the country's welfare system and public sector, including France's state-owned railway company SNCF. May 1's shadow: The government deployed 2,000 police to observe the demonstrations after an estimated 1,000 people vandalized shops and cars in Paris during May 1 protests. More than 100 people were arrested after those rallies. Read more: Emmanuel Macron: A republican 'Sun King' whose popularity is not setting France's new 'Sun King': Some French commentators have criticized Macron for his leadership style. After the president referred to the French as "my people" in an interview in December, French newspaper Le Monde compared him to French absolute monarch Louis XIV, the "Sun King," who ruled for 72 years in the 17th and early 18th century. Where was Monsieur Macron? The French president was on the other side of the world on Saturday. He was visiting the Pacific island of New Caledonia, a French territory. Read more: Emmanuel Macron: 'France is back as a European reformer' Send  Facebook   Twitter   google+   Whatsapp   Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2wj0v amp, ls/aw (AFP, AP, dpa)